Requirements are gathered and documented through a structured delivery approach based on implementation best practices, business alignment principles, and controlled project governance using Azure DevOps (ADO).

The process begins with discovery workshops involving key business stakeholders to understand current operations, pain points, future objectives, and operational constraints. Sessions are focused on identifying business needs rather than immediately defining technical solutions.

Once the business need is understood, requirements are translated into clear functional statements describing the capability required from the system. Priority, business impact, dependencies, risks, and expected outcomes are also defined during this stage.

Each requirement is documented using a standardized structure including business objective, current process, proposed future process, actors, business flow, business rules, assumptions, scope, and acceptance criteria. This ensures consistency and clarity across all workstreams.

Requirements are then reviewed jointly with business users, functional leads, and technical teams to validate feasibility, identify standard platform capabilities, and determine genuine gaps requiring design or development.

Approved requirements are converted into ADO work items such as Epics, Features, User Stories, Tasks, and Test Cases, maintaining full traceability from initial demand through design, build, testing, user acceptance, and production release.

This methodology ensures strong governance, stakeholder alignment, delivery transparency, reduced ambiguity, and successful implementation outcomes in enterprise retail environments.

The functional-requirements branch contains practical examples of business and system requirements documented using a structured methodology based on industry best practices and Microsoft delivery standards.

These examples demonstrate how business needs are translated into clear functional requirements, including objective, business process flow, actors, rules, scope, assumptions, and expected outcomes.

The branch is intended to showcase professional requirement management practices, business analysis capabilities, and functional consulting experience within retail and enterprise implementation projects.
